  abstract = {One of the most important and difficult problems now confronting city planners is the development of accurate, usable techniques for estimating the current daytime population of census tracts in metropolitan areas. Such estimates differ greatly from the population statistics known to planners in the past. They per- tain to daytime rather than residential population - to the number of persons gathered in a given area at a specific time during the day, rather than the number with residence in an area. Estimates are given separately by census tract or comparable geo- graphic area, for both central cities and adjacent urbanized territory. They refer to a current or post- censal date instead of the time at which the most recent Federal census or other survey was taken. These estimates accordingly show little resemblance to conventional population statistics. The need for current daytime population esti- mates is found in many presentday planning prob- lems. In civil defense, for example, such estimates are necessary for developing evacuation procedures, planning the location and size of bomb shelters, and approximating the number of potential (or actual) casualties resulting from atomic attacks. Uptodate figures on daytime population distribution are use- ful also in analyses of thoroughfare, public transit, parking, shopping center, and public utility needs. Similar problems occur in the field of market research},
